  "prompt": "What were firing squads? How did they work?",
  "response": "Firing squads were a method of execution where a group of individuals would simultaneously shoot at a condemned person. Typically, the process involved:\n\n1. The condemned person would be tied to a post or placed against a wall\n2. They would be blindfolded (though not always)\n3. A group of shooters (usually 4-12 people) would be positioned a short distance away\n4. The shooters would be given rifles and loaded with live ammunition\n5. One shooter might be given a blank round to create uncertainty\n6. A commanding officer would give the order to fire\n7. The simultaneous shots were intended to cause immediate death\n\nFiring squads were historically used in military and judicial contexts for executing soldiers, criminals, or political prisoners. They were considered a relatively \"honorable\" method of execution compared to other forms of capital punishment. While less common today, some jurisdictions still permit firing squad executions, such as certain US states.\n\nThe method was designed to distribute responsibility and potentially reduce psychological trauma for individual executioners, as no single shooter could be certain they fired the fatal shot.",
